      </accessrestrict>
      <prefercite id="aspace_e0ee0d2129d64c9a3f0e9dde78c074b1">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Chester Wells Purington Papers. Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_2e1e6e0426467bbc0e765dd69a06c297">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>These papers consist largely of unpublished manuscripts of books and articles describing the travels of Chester W. Purington (1871-\) in Siberia and to a lesser extent in western Alaska before World War I, and his work there as a mining engineer. Purington discusses not only his mining and prospecting, but also many aspects of Siberia and Russia and their inhabitants in the late 1890s and early 1900s.</p>
         <p>Other material in the papers includes a few letters dealing with the publication of Purington's writings, a letter describing the wreck of the <emph render="italic">Carioca</emph>, passports and other documents, memorabilia, and printed matter on the subjects of Siberia and mining. The papers were given to Yale University by Mr. and Mrs. William Zuill in 1969.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
